subSubSection.paragraph:
Head. Ant IV with four leaf-shaped sensilla (
Fig. 3A
), and a more or less broad and pointed modified chaeta near the base (
Fig. 3B
). Paired sensilla of Ant III sensory organ (
Fig. 3D
) leaf or paddle shaped; segment proximally with modified cylindrical and pointed chaeta (
Fig. 3E
); Ant II with 12 expanded chaetae (
Fig. 3G
). Ant I with seven expanded chaetae. Eyes absent; PAO with single small vesicle (
Fig. 3H
). Postlabial chaetae slightly basally swollen (
Fig 3H
), six along the cephalic groove.

Legs. External face of leg 2 tibiotarsus with spatulated chaetae characteristic of the genus (
Fig. 3J
); tibiotarsus on all legs with large ciliated chaetae (
Fig. 3K
); claw with inner edge smooth, with pseudonychia on basal two thirds of claw; empodial appendage smooth, external lamela without teeth (
Fig. 3L, 3M
).

Furca. Tenaculum with four teeth and one chaeta on the corpus (
Fig. 3I
).

Dental segmentation incomplete, with a four-toothed inner proximal spine, one two or three toothed internal distal spines (more or less falcate) and one large, slightly spinate, external distal falcate spines. Mucro with four teeth: two apical, one medial and one basal, sharp, between them a wavy membranous crest (
Figs 3N, 3O
).
